While the traditional Labour Day Classic game is always played on the Sunday before [[Labour Day]] at [[Mosaic Stadium at Taylor Field]] in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]], there is usually a rematch on the following weekend between these two rival [[Canadian Prairies|prairie]] teams at [[Canad Inns Stadium]] in [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]].
The "Banjo Bowl" moniker was coined by Blue Bombers board member [[David Asper]] in early 2004, inspired by an infamous comment made by Bombers [[placekicker]] [[Troy Westwood]] in the week prior to a [[2003 CFL season|2003]] Western Division Semi-final game between the two teams. Westwood was quoted in the media as saying that people from Regina were "a bunch of [[banjo]]-pickin' [[inbred]]s."<ref>{{cite web | url = http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Football/CFL/Winnipeg/2006/09/09/1818545-sun.html | accessdate = 2009-09-13 | title = Evolution of the Banjo Bowl | first = Kirk | last = Penton | publisher = [[Winnipeg Sun]] | date = September 9, 2006}}</ref> He later apologized half-heartedly for those comments, saying that "the vast majority of the people in Saskatchewan have no idea how to play the banjo."<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Terry|title=Labour Pains|publisher=Calgary Sun|date=September 2, 2007|page=S11|url=http://calsun.canoe.ca/Sports/Football/2007/09/02/4464824-sun.html|accessdate=2007-09-02}}</ref> This further fueled the WinnipegâSaskatchewan football rivalry and has made the rematch game even more of an event. The game is sponsored by the [[Manitoba Lotteries Corporation]]. The game has been sold out every year since 2005. As of the 2011 season, the series is tied 4-4.
As on Labour Day weekend when many Winnipeg fans visit Regina to support the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers|Bombers]], many Saskatchewan fans visit Winnipeg the following weekend to support the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders|'Riders]]. Many come, tongue-in-cheek, with banjos.
